Basic File & Directory Commands:
pwd                 # Show current directory
ls                  # List files in current directory
ls -l               # List with details (permissions, size, date)
ls -a               # List all, including hidden files
cd /path/to/dir     # Change directory
mkdir new_folder    # Create new directory
rmdir folder_name   # Remove empty directory

File Operations:
touch file.txt                 # Create empty file
cp file1.txt file2.txt         # Copy file
mv file1.txt /path/to/dir/     # Move file
mv old.txt new.txt             # Rename file
rm file.txt                    # Delete file
rm -r folder/                  # Delete folder and contents
cat file.txt                   # View file content
nano file.txt                  # Edit file (nano editor)

Permissions & Ownership:
ls -l                          # Show file permissions
chmod 755 file.sh              # Change file permissions
chown user:user file.txt       # Change file owner

System Information:
whoami                         # Show current user
uname -a                       # Show system info
df -h                          # Show disk usage
free -h                        # Show memory usage
top                            # Show running processes
htop                           # Better process viewer (if installed)
dduser newuser                 # Add new user
passwd newuser                 # Change user password
su - newuser                   # Switch user
groups                         # Show groups
usermod -aG sudo newuser       # Add user to sudo group


Networking:
ifconfig            # Show network interfaces (use `ip a` if not installed)
ping google.com     # Test connectivity
curl ifconfig.me    # Show public IP
ssh user@host       # Connect to remote server
scp file.txt user@host:/path/   # Copy file to remote server
wget http://example.com/file     # Download file

Package Management (Ubuntu/Debian):
sudo apt update                  # Update package list
sudo apt upgrade                 # Upgrade packages
sudo apt install package_name    # Install package
sudo apt remove package_name     # Uninstall package

Processes & Services:
ps aux | grep process_name       # Find process
kill -9 PID                      # Kill process
systemctl status service         # Check service status
systemctl start service          # Start service
systemctl stop service           # Stop service
systemctl restart service        # Restart service
systemctl enable service         # Enable at boot

Disk & Storage:
lsblk                            # List disks
mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt             # Mount drive
umount /mnt                      # Unmount drive
df -h                            # Show mounted disks
du -h --max-depth=1 /path        # Disk usage per folder

AWS-Specific (CLI):
aws configure                    # Configure AWS CLI
aws s3 ls                        # List S3 buckets
aws s3 mb s3://my-bucket         # Create bucket
aws s3 cp file.txt s3://my-bucket/   # Upload file to S3
aws s3 sync . s3://my-bucket     # Sync folder to S3

aws ec2 describe-instances       # List EC2 instances
aws ec2 start-instances --instance-ids i-1234567890abcdef
aws ec2 stop-instances --instance-ids i-1234567890abcdef

aws iam list-users               # List IAM users
aws rds describe-db-instances    # List RDS instances

